mainmatter.p:
Given a pair of adjoint functor F  \dashv  G, G  \circ  F forms a monad. As a converse, we can consider the adjunctions whose composition is a given monad M. These decompositions form a bicategory. The morphisms between two adjunctions are given by functors L that make the two triangles below commute.


      \usepackage{mlmodern, tikz, tikz-cd, quiver, mathtools, amssymb, stmaryrd, mathrsfs}

   \begin {tikzcd} 
  { \mathcal { D } _2} & { \mathcal { D } _1} & { \mathcal { C } }
   \arrow [shift right, from=1-2, to=1-3]
   \arrow [shift right, from=1-3, to=1-2]
   \arrow [shift right, curve={height=18pt}, from=1-1, to=1-3]
   \arrow [shift right, curve={height=18pt}, from=1-3, to=1-1]
   \arrow ["L", from=1-2, to=1-1]
 \end {tikzcd}


More precisely, the objects of this bicategory are given by adjunctions F  \dashv  G together with a natural isomorphism G  \circ  F  \cong  M. A morphism from F_1  \dashv  G_1 to F_2  \dashv  G_2 is given by a functor L together with two natural isomorphisms L  \circ  G_1  \cong  G_2, F_1  \cong  F_2  \circ  L. A 2-morphism is given by a natural transformation such that the relevant composition of natural transformations are equal.

We verify that they form an adjunction. Algebra homomorphisms \varphi : F_M X \to Y are given by commutative squares
\usepackage{mlmodern, tikz, tikz-cd, quiver, mathtools, amssymb, stmaryrd, mathrsfs}
\begin {tikzcd} %tex {M^2 X} & MY \\ MX & Y \arrow["{\alpha_Y}", from=1-2, to=2-2] \arrow["\mu"', from=1-1, to=2-1] \arrow["\varphi", from=2-1, to=2-2] \arrow["{M\varphi}", from=1-1, to=1-2] \end {tikzcd}
while morphisms f : X \to Y fits in the diagram as such:
\usepackage{mlmodern, tikz, tikz-cd, quiver, mathtools, amssymb, stmaryrd, mathrsfs}
\begin {tikzcd} %tex {M^2 X} & MY \\ MX & Y \\ X \arrow["{\alpha_Y}", from=1-2, to=2-2] \arrow["\mu"', from=1-1, to=2-1] \arrow["\varphi", from=2-1, to=2-2] \arrow["{M\varphi}", from=1-1, to=1-2] \arrow["f"', from=3-1, to=2-2] \arrow["\eta", from=3-1, to=2-1] \arrow[from=2-1, to=1-2] \end {tikzcd}
Given a homomorphism \varphi of algebras, we can compute f by composing with \eta. On the other hand, given f, we define \varphi by \alpha _Y \circ Mf. This creates a commutative square because \begin {aligned} \alpha _Y \circ M \varphi &= \alpha _Y \circ M \alpha _Y \circ M^2 f \\ &= \alpha _Y \circ \mu \circ M^2 f \\ &= \alpha _Y \circ M f \circ \mu \\ &= \varphi \circ \mu . \end {aligned}
